                        <name key="Sapindaceae">Sapindaceae</name>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="">
                           <name key="Anacardiaceae">Anacardiaceae</name>
                        </seg>
                        <seg style="">
                           <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                              <p rend="Footnote"
                                 style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                                 xml:lang="en">
                                 <seg style="">
                                    <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                                    <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                                 </seg>A series of dots has been added beneath <name key="Hypericineae">Hypericineae</name>, <name key="Simarubeae">Simarubeae</name>, <name key="Meliaceae">Meliaceae</name> and <name key="Sapindaceae">Sapindaceae</name>.</p>
                           </note>
                        </seg>
                     </p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>All which I hope to include in the 1st vol.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With regard to your view about species you seem to have taken a wrong view of mine[.] I had for a great many years during my continued observation of living plants in a great variety of stations in almost every country of Europe devoted much attention to the subject and had come more and more to the conclusion that species had fixed limits <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">difficult as it is often to find them</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; "> </seg>and that genera and Orders were arbitrary — and though I never wrote much on the subject I collected a great number of facts — and explained my views somewhat generally about genera in a Memorandum published in one of the first vols. of the Journal of the Linnean Society and I believe in a review of De Candolle's Geographie Botanique in the Edinburgh Review.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1858) &amp; Bentham (1856).</p>
               </note> But I entered much more in detail into the question of species in a paper read at the Linnean Society in Nov 1858 but which circumstances prevented the publication at the time, but 2½ years later it was inserted in the first vol. of the Natural History Review<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1861b).</p>
               </note> — I had no separate copies of this paper — I have not even one for myself — or I should have sent it you but I have no doubt you have the work. It was immediately after the reading of this paper that Darwin's remarkable observations were first made known — and whatever may be one's opinion of the speculative part of his work, it is very certain that the numerous facts he has observed must cause naturalists to reconsider their previous opinions, and I begin to think that my former views of the fixity of species must be in some measure modified — or at least exceptions admitted — But however that may be, if species are fixed, the evidence of what is a species and what is a race is <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">never positive</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M has interlined an annotation: (Whatever is not positive is not specific F.M.)<seg style="font-style: italic; ">.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg> — always more or less circumstantial and therefore differently appreciated by different minds — and there is no hope of establishing the limits of species so as to admit of no dispute even on the part of the most experienced most acute and most right-judging botanists — without even taking into account that all men tend to attach undue importance to evidence discovered by themselves over that which others have brought forward.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I yesterday went through Brown's <name key="Tremandreae">Tremandreae</name> and <name key="Polygaleae">Polygaleae</name> — there was nothing in the former but five sets of queries I had already — in <name key="Polygaleae">Polygaleae</name> he had Salomonia oblongif.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M has interlined an annotation: i.e. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Salomonia%20oblongifolia">Salomonia oblongifolia</name>
                     </seg>. (Flinders voy) F.M..</p>
               </note> from Endeavour River — I had noted that it was Australian but somehow had forgotten on what grounds and should have omitted it again if I had not seen these. — He has also excellent specimens of your <name key="Comesperma%20defoliatum">Comesperma defoliatum</name> from P. Jackson &amp; Hunter's river<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Both in NSW.</p>
               </note> which we have not at Kew<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Australian collections made by <seg style="">Robert Brown (1773-1858) </seg>were held by the British Museum.</p>
               </note> a new tropical Comesperma in the way of scoparium and a K.G.S.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>King George Sound, WA</p>
               </note> one allied to calymega but with rather longer flowers and very differently shaped fruits. I have not yet seen your C. spinosum — but of course all the Orders I do before your specimens arrive must be gone over again with them which is as well as it serves to check blunders doing things at twice at some interval.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Gypsophila%20tubulosa">Gypsophila tubulosa</name> must be indigenous Brown found it on Cooks River and Nepean River and it could not then have established itself there from the Levant</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope you are at work at the second volume of your Victorian Flora and that you will keep publishing that work ahead of me not only as the best way of securing to yourself the priority and credit of your observations, but as a depot of detailed information which there will be no room for in my work, and yet necessary for Victorian Botanists </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The remainder of the letter was filed with G. Bentham to M, 24 March 1862. It could not have been written in March, as it responds to issues raised in M to G. Bentham, 23 May 1862.</p>
               </note>No 18 of your Fragmenta which you mention<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B62.05.01; see M to G. Bentham, 23 May 1862.</p>
               </note> has not yet come to hand — Your specimens of <name key="Streptothamnus">Streptothamnus</name> are received — I do not know what to make of them — I have as yet nothing like a climber in <name key="Bixineae">Bixineae</name> — If at all of that order it comes into <name key="Oncobe%C3%A6">Oncobeæ</name> but is very unlike them.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your <name key="Gunnia">Gunnia</name> had been overlooked — that is originally laid aside as not belonging to <name key="Portulaceae">Portulaceae</name> proper but to <name key="Tetragonieae">Tetragonieae</name> I had forgotten to mention it among Genera exclusion<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. not included in the list of 'Genera affinia aut exclusa, v. dubia', <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol. 1, p. 156. See M to G. Bentham, 23 May 1862, for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Gunnia">Gunnia</name>
                     </seg> and the other topics in this and the next paragraphs.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have this morning been at Polycarpaeae of which we have besides your very good specimens from Armstrong<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>John Armstrong, d. 1847.</p>
               </note> Cunningham Macgillivray and Bynoe — all your species and from the N.W. Coast the 8 Indian and Arabian P. spicata.<note xml:id="ftn15" type="footnote" n="15">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Polycarpaea%20spicata">Polycarpaea spicata</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> I make out nine Australian species, that is three <name key="Planchonia">Planchonia</name>s (Gay) with the petals connate in a tube with the stamens two <name key="Aylmerias">Aylmerias</name> free petals and staminodia — and four <name key="Polycarpaceae">Polycarpaceae</name> proper — Tomorrow I begin upon <name key="Portulaceae">Portulaceae</name> — that is <name key="Portulaca">Portulaca</name>
               <name key="Calandrinia">Calandrinia</name> and <name key="Claytonia">Claytonia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">Sir William has just received no 18 of your Fragmenta.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I see in No 17<note xml:id="ftn16" type="footnote" n="16">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B62.04.01.</p>
               </note> you have two new <name key="Anonaceae">Anonaceae</name> Your <name key="Uvaria%20heteropetala">Uvaria heteropetala</name> from your characters is different from the only Australian Uvaria I have, one from Cape York McGillivray which I have called U. membranacea — but is not your <name key="Unona%20nitens">Unona nitens</name> the same as U. nitidissima Dun. or U. fulgens Labill. Sert. Austro. Caled.<note xml:id="ftn17" type="footnote" n="17">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See Labillardière (1824-5), p. 57, tab. 56.</p>
               </note> of which there are specimens from Queensland in Cunningham's collections and also in some others — and which is not a true Unona but a <name key="Polyalthia">Polyalthia</name> having only 1 or 2 erect ovules in each carpel and not several as figured by mistake by Labillardiere. I have very carefully examined Labillardiere's own specimens as well as the Moreton Bay ones.</p>
